A camera is an optical instrument used to capture an image. At their most basic, cameras are sealed boxes (the camera body) with a small hole (the aperture) that allow light in to capture an image on a light-sensitive surface (usually photographic film or a digital sensor). Cameras have various mechanisms to control how the light falls onto the light-sensitive surface. Lenses focus the light entering the camera, the size of the aperture can be widened or narrowed to let more or less light into the camera, and a shutter mechanism determines the amount of time the photo-sensitive surface is exposed to the light.¶

In this project the dataset will be about cameras, their specifications, types, and date of release. The data were collected from 1994 to 2007.¶

Now that we have reviewed the quality of the data and made the necessary adjustments to it, we will define the units of numerical data and explain some of the terms contained in the data.¶

Since there are no specific units, we will assume each of the following:¶

-Resolution: Megapixel

-Zoom: Millimetre (mm)

-Focus Range: Millimetre (mm)

-Storage: GB

-Weight: Gram (G)

-Dimensions: Millimetre (mm)

-Price: Dollar ($)

Explain some of the terms contained in the data¶

Resolution: The image resolution is the detail an image holds. The term applies to raster digital images, film images, and other types of images. Higher resolution means more image detail.¶

Effective pixels: Are the pixels that capture the image data. They are effective and by definition, effective means "successful in producing the desired effect or intended result." These are the pixels that are doing the work of capturing a picture¶

Zoom wide: W - Wide (more details in the same picture)¶

Zoom tele: T - Telephoto. (less detail but you get close to the subject).¶

Focus range: The minimum focus distance is the shortest distance at which a lens can focus, and the more millimeters, the bigger the dimensions of the image.¶

Well, now before performing the analysis, we will take into consideration the following characteristics:¶

-Max_resolution

-Effective_pixels

-Low_resolution

They are the features that make the picture better, so the higher the numbers, the more professional the camera, We will call these Specifications: "professional Specifications".

And Given that the use of cameras is very multiple to some users, like a camera's weight and its ability to fit in a pocket may be more important factors than its resolution for them, we will focus on our analyzing the specifications that make the camera more professional.¶

2- What are the The percentage of most frequent companies?

In [12]:
# plot the frequent companies
# write the code:

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 10), subplot_kw=dict(aspect="equal"))

companies = ['7 Agfa',
             '115 Canon',
             '63 Casio',
             '2 Contax', '15 Epson', '99 Fujifilm', '46 HP',
       '2 JVC', '102 Kodak', '15 Kyocera', '11 Leica', '90 Nikon', '122 Olympus',
       '55 Panasonic', '68 Pentax', '26 Ricoh', '54 Samsung', '8 Sanyo', '4 Sigma',
       '116 Sony', '18 Toshiba']

data = [float(x.split()[0]) for x in companies]
ingredients = [x.split()[-1] for x in companies]


def func(pct, allvals):
    absolute = int(pct/100.*np.sum(allvals))
    return "{:.1f}%\n({:d} )".format(pct, absolute)

plt.xticks(rotation = 90);
wedges, texts, autotexts = ax.pie(data, autopct=lambda pct: func(pct, data),
                                  textprops=dict(color="k"))

ax.legend(wedges, ingredients,
          title="manufacturer",
          loc="center left",
          bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0, 0.5, 1))

plt.setp(autotexts, size=10, weight="bold")

ax.set_title("The percentage of of most frequent companies")

plt.show()

Here we see that with the passage of years the prices of cameras increase, in 1994 the prices were the lowest and continue to grow until 2007, which is the last year in our data set.¶

Of course, this increase in prices is due to the development of cameras and the development of specifications at all levels.¶

3- How has specifications evolved over the years?¶

In [26]:
# write the code:
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
#make a subplot of size 3,3.
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,3,figsize = (12,8))

#set the title of the subplot.
fig.suptitle('The evolution of specifications over the years',fontsize = 16)

#plot
df.groupby('Release_date').mean()['Max_resolution'].plot(label='Max resolution' ,color='#00818a',ax = ax[0][0],legend=True)
df.groupby('Release_date').mean()['Low_resolution'].plot(label = "Low resolution",color='#db3b61',ax = ax[0][1],legend=True)
df.groupby('Release_date').mean()['Effective_pixels'].plot(label = "Effective pixels",color='#33FFB5',ax = ax[0][2],legend=True)
df.groupby('Release_date').mean()['Zoom_wide'].plot(label = "Zoom wide",color='c',ax = ax[1][0],legend=True)
df.groupby('Release_date').mean()['Zoom_tele'].plot(label = "Zoom tele",color='#f67280',ax = ax[1][1],legend=True)
df.groupby('Release_date').mean()['Normal_focus_range'].plot(label = "Normal focus range",color='#1a2c5b',ax = ax[1][2],legend=True)
Out[26]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fb6dfd85e80>

Max resolution: this property developed tremendously in 1995 and then fell back sharply after that, but since 1997 it has returned gradually and progressively.¶

Low resolution: evolution was growing in them almost exponentially.¶

Effective pixels: As happened with Max resolution, this property evolved tremendously in 1995 and then decreased, but it gradually developed again.¶

Zoom wide (W): In 1996 it also developed terribly, but after that it decreased slightly and continues to fluctuate at an almost constant rate between high and low, evolving over the years, and perhaps this is because this property is not widely used.¶

Zoom tele (T): The evolution in it was growing in an almost ascending order.¶

Normal focus range: As is the case with Zoom wide, it was highest in 1996 and then fell back slightly and then oscillated relatively steadily.¶

Conclusion¶

This data was collected by Some camera enthusiast and described 1,000 cameras based on 13 properties.¶

In this project, we explained some of the camera-related specifications, sorted the most popular companies in the dataset, and classified the models in terms of prices, professional specifications, weight relationship to those specifications, and lastly how these specifications have evolved over the years.¶
